{"query": "reference-free ASR evaluation ICASSP Interspeech 2024 2025", "follow_up_questions": null, "answer": null, "images": [], "results": [{"url": "https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2", "title": "Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge", "content": "In the subjective evaluation, some generative approaches were preferred over the top system based on the discriminative model.\nNote that we conducted subjective evaluations only on English data due to the time constraint of the Interspeech challenge.\nGenerative models are expected not to hallucinate the content heavily on English data as the majority of the training data was English.\nSince P.808 is a reference-free absolute category rating test where the prompt was “How do you rate the overall quality of the following speech sample?”, it would be difficult to penalize the correctness of the spoken content and speaker consistency as long as the speech sounds natural. [...] In this section, we report the evaluation results of the submitted systems.\nWe also provide some preliminary analysis based on the brief system descriptions we collected from participants.\n\n### 4.1 Overall results\n\nTable 2 shows the evaluation results, where 12 out of 22 systems submitted to Track1 (T\\) and 4 out of 10 systems submitted to Track2 (S\\) are shown due to space limitations.\nThe full results are available on our leaderboard999.\nD, G, and D+G in ‘Model type’ cell denote discriminative, generative, and hybrid (e.g., discriminative model with adversarial loss or cascade of discriminative and generative models), respectively.\nT10 and T22 are the baseline system and noisy audios, respectively. [...] ## 6 Acknowledgement\n\nThis work was partially supported by JSPS KAKENHI Grant Number JP24KJ2096.\nThe leaderboard evaluation has been supported by the PSC Bridges2 system via ACCESS allocation CIS210014, supported by National Science Foundation grants #2138259, #2138286, #2138307, #2137603, and #2138296.\nThe subjective listening test was funded and executed by Technische Universität Braunschweig.\n\n## References\n\nMascot Sammy", "score": 0.6854659, "raw_content": "Saijo\nZhang\nCornell\nScheibler\nLi\nNi\nKumar\nSach\nFu\nWang\nFingscheidt\nWatanabe\nWaseda University, Japan\n2Shanghai Jiao Tong University, China\n3Carnegie Mellon University, USA\n4Google DeepMind, Japan\n5Meta, USA\n6Technische Universität BraunschweigGermany\n\n# Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\n\n###### Abstract\n\nThere has been a growing effort to develop universal speech enhancement (SE) to handle inputs with various speech distortions and recording conditions. The URGENT Challenge series aims to foster such universal SE by embracing a broad range of distortion types, increasing data diversity, and incorporating extensive evaluation metrics. This work introduces the Interspeech 2025 URGENT Challenge, the second edition of the series, to explore several aspects that have received limited attention so far: language dependency, universality for more distortion types, data scalability, and the effectiveness of using noisy training data. We received 32 submissions, where the best system uses a discriminative model, while most other competitive ones are hybrid methods. Analysis reveals some key findings: (i) some generative or hybrid approaches are preferred in subjective evaluations over the top discriminative model, and (ii) purely generative SE models can exhibit language dependency.\n\n###### keywords:\n\n## 1 Introduction\n\nSpeech enhancement (SE) aims to improve speech quality degraded by noise, reverberation, or other distortions.\nIt has seen significant progress thanks to neural networks.\nHowever, most prior work has focused on matched training–inference conditions and limited tasks such as noise suppression and dereverberation.\n\nIn recent years, the advent of generative models has broadened the scope of SE to include more complex tasks such as bandwidth extension, packet loss concealment [[1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib1)], and wind noise reduction [[2](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib2)].\nFollowing this trend, there has been growing interest in developing universal SE models capable of handling multiple tasks and diverse input formats within a single framework.\nFor example, score-based diffusion models have been explored for universal SE [[3](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib3), [4](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib4)], enabling a single model to address multiple SE tasks.\nTo support diverse input formats, models that process multiple sampling rates and varying numbers of microphones have also been proposed [[5](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib5)].\nHowever, despite these advances, a well-established benchmark for evaluating generative and universal SE models remains lacking, making fair comparisons challenging.\n\nTo address this gap, the URGENT Challenge (Universality, Robustness, and Generalizability of speech EnhancemeNT) was launched.\nThe first edition, the URGENT 2024 Challenge [[6](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib6)], aimed to lay the foundation for developing universal SE models by setting two key objectives: (i) handling four types of distortion (additive noise, reverberation, bandwidth limitation, and clipping) and (ii) accommodating input signals with varying sampling rates.\nThe challenge utilized a collection of publicly available datasets, significantly larger than those used in most prior studies, and employed a comprehensive evaluation framework with as many as 13 evaluation metrics.\n\nTo further advance the development of universal SE models, we propose the second edition of the series, Interspeech 2025 URGENT Challenge.\nThis iteration introduces the following modifications based on our preliminary investigations [[7](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib7)]:\n\nMore data diversity: There is room for improvement in robustness on, e.g., samples with unseen or rarely seen noise. To address this, the proposed challenge by incorporating more diverse speech and noise data.\n\nLeveraging noisy data: While noisy data is crucial for scaling up the amount of data due to the scarcity of clean data, we found that simple filtering methods (e.g., using DNSMOS scores [[8](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib8)]) did not remove noisy samples very effectively. We intentionally include more noisy data to encourage participants to explore effective ways of utilizing it.\n\nTwo tracks with different training data scales: To examine the impact of data scale, the proposed challenge introduces two tracks with different training data sizes: one with ∼similar-to\\sim∼2.5k hours and the other with ∼similar-to\\sim∼60k hours of speech..\n\nMore distortions: We found that SE models struggle to generalize to unseen distortions. To enhance generalizability, we consider three additional distortions, commonly observed in real recordings due to the recording device or environment.\n\nMultilingual data: While the first challenge used only English data, the proposed challenge incorporates multilingual data, allowing us to examine the accessibility of SE models and evaluation metrics across the languages.\n\nThe challenge has received 22 submissions for one track and 10 for the other.\nThis paper details the challenge design and presents a preliminary analysis of the submissions.\nThe details of the challenge are also available on our website111<https://urgent-challenge.github.io/urgent2025/>.\n\n## 2 Related works\n\nExisting SE challenges have greatly advanced SE studies for specific scenarios, such as denoising and dereverberation [[9](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib9), [10](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib10)], speech restoration [[11](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib11), [12](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib12)], packet loss concealment [[1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib1)], and so on.\nThe URGENT challenge complements existing ones by focusing on universality, generalizability, and robustness across diverse scenarios and evaluation metrics.\n\nMost previous SE studies use only monolingual data, and thus language dependency of SE models is still under-explored.\nWhile the language dependency of discriminative SE has been reported to be small [[13](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib13)], that of generative SE lacks thorough investigation.\nAdditionally, although often overlooked, some metrics can be language dependent [[14](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib14), [15](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib15)].\nThrough this challenge, we collect the objective and subjective evaluation scores of various SE systems in multiple languages, which will later be analyzed to assess the language dependency of metrics222We were able to collect the subjective listening scores only on English data during the challenge period due to the Interspeech challenge time constraint. We plan to collect data for other languages and analyze the metrics after the challenge concludes..\n\nOne of the focuses of this challenge is how to leverage possibly noisy data.\nWhile there are some possible approaches such as data filtering based on non-intrusive SE metrics [[8](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib8), [16](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib16), [17](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib17)] or unsupervised learning [[18](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib18), [19](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib19)], a comprehensive comparison of them is currently lacking, particularly on large-scale data.\nThe proposed challenge aims to clarify which of these methods are more effective, or if new ones can be devised, by encouraging participants to explore how to leverage noisy data.\n\nThis challenge also explores the impact of training data size on final performance.\nWhile this has been investigated in other fields [[20](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib20), [21](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib21)], to our best knowledge, only an investigation on small-scale data has been done in SE field [[22](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib22)].\nThe proposed challenge offers two tracks with different data amounts, encouraging the investigation of data scalability.\n\n## 3 Challenge Design\n\n### 3.1 Task definition\n\nIn the URGENT challenge, the SE process is defined as [[6](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib6)]:\n\n|  |  |  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  | 𝐱^^𝐱\\displaystyle\\hat{\\mathbf{x}}over^ start\\_ARG bold\\_x end\\_ARG | =SE⁡(ℱ⁢(𝐱)),absentSEℱ𝐱\\displaystyle=\\operatorname{SE}(\\mathcal{F}(\\mathbf{x}))\\,,= roman\\_SE ( caligraphic\\_F ( bold\\_x ) ) , |  | (1) |\n\nwhere 𝐱𝐱\\mathbf{x}bold\\_x and 𝐱^^𝐱\\hat{\\mathbf{x}}over^ start\\_ARG bold\\_x end\\_ARG are the desired and enhanced speech signals.\nℱ⁢(⋅)ℱ⋅\\mathcal{F}(\\cdot)caligraphic\\_F ( ⋅ ) is the distortion model that degrades the desired signal.\nOur definition differs from the commonly adopted one in the literature in that the SE model has to handle\n(i) inputs with *various sampling frequencies (SF)* (8, 16, 22.05, 24, 32, 44.1, and 48kHz), while most existing SE systems often only consider a fixed SF,\n(ii) inputs with *seven types of distortions* (detailed in Section [3.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.SS2 \"3.2 Distortions ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\")), while most existing SE systems consider only noise or reverberation, and\n(iii) multilingual speech, while most existing SE studies consider only monolingual data.\n\n### 3.2 Distortions\n\nThe challenge considers the following seven distortions in the distortion model ℱℱ\\mathcal{F}caligraphic\\_F: additive noise, reverberation, clipping, bandwidth limitation, codec loss (MP3 and OGG), packet loss, and wind noise333We used the wind-noise simulator provided in [[2](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib2)]: <https://github.com/sp-uhh/storm>, which is based on <https://github.com/audiolabs/SC-Wind-Noise-Generator>.\nCompared to the first challenge, which included only the first four distortions [[6](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib6)], the present challenge introduces three more challenging but realistic conditions.\nEach noisy speech is degraded by up to five distortions simultaneously.\n\n### 3.3 Data\n\n|  |  |  |\n| --- | --- | --- |\n| Type | Corpus | Duration |\n| Speech | LibriVox data from DNS5 Challenge (en) [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib10)] | ~350 h |\n| LibriTTS reading speech (en) [[23](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib23)] | ~200 h |\n| VCTK reading speech (en) [[24](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib24)] | ~80 h |\n| WSJ reading speech (en) [[25](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib25), [26](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib26)] | ~85 h |\n| EARS expressive speech (en) [[27](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib27)] | ~107 h |\n| MLS-HQ◆ (en, de, fr, es) [[28](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib28)] | ~450 (48600) h |\n| CommonVoice 19.0 (en, de, fr, es, zn)  [[29](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib29)] | ~1300 (9500) h |\n| Noise | Noise from DNS5 Challenge [[10](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib10)] | ~180 h |\n| WHAM! noise [[30](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib30)] | ~70 h |\n| FSD50K [[31](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib31)] | ~100 h |\n| Free Music Archive (FMA, Medium partition) [[32](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib32)] | ~200 h |\n| Wind noise simulated by participants | - |\n| \\hdashline\\rowcolor[HTML]EEEEEE | DEMAND [[33](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib33)] | - |\n| \\rowcolor[HTML]EEEEEE | TUT Urban Acoustic Scenes 2018 [[34](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib34)] | - |\n| RIR | Simulated RIRs from DNS5 Challenge | ~60k samples |\n| Other RIRs simulated by participants | - |\n| \\hdashline\\rowcolor[HTML]EEEEEE | SLR28 real RIRs | - |\n| \\rowcolor[HTML]EEEEEE | BRUDEX [[35](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib35)] | - |\n| \\rowcolor[HTML]EEEEEE | MYRiAD V2 econ [[36](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib36)] | - |\n\n#### 3.3.1 Training data\n\nA collection of public corpora listed in Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\") is used as training data.\nParticipants can freely simulate noisy speech using these data.\nIt is also allowed to freely simulate distortions mentioned in Section [3.2](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.SS2 \"3.2 Distortions ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\").\nHowever, to allow a fair comparison, using datasets other than those listed in Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\") is prohibited.\n\nAs some speech corpora include noisy speech, we preprocessed them following the methodology of the first challenge [[6](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib6)].\nSpecifically, for DNS5 Challenge data and CommonVoice, we (i) resampled the speech to the lowest SF that can fully cover the effective frequency range, (ii) filtered out non-speech or samples dominated by silence using voice activity detection (VAD) 666<https://github.com/wiseman/py-webrtcvad>, and (iii) filtered out noisy samples based on the DNSMOS score [[8](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib8)].\nWe also applied the resampling process to LibriTTS, MLS-HQ, DNS noise, FSD50K, and FMA.\n\nNote that the VAD- and DNSMOS-based data filtering mentioned above is imperfect.\nIndeed, we found many samples with audible background noise still remaining after the data filtering.\nAlthough such noisy samples may adversely affect SE model training, we intentionally keep such samples to encourage participants to explore how to leverage noisy samples effectively.\n\nTo investigate the language dependency of SE models, we use two multilingual corpora, MLS-HQ777We prepared the high-quality version of MLS (MLS-HQ) by crawling less-compressed speech from LibriVox (<https://librivox.org>) and segmenting them using the same timestamps as MLS. and CommonVoice 19.0 which cover five languages in total (en, de, fr, es, and zn).\n\n#### 3.3.2 Validation/non-blind test data\n\nIn the challenge, it is allowed to freely simulate participants’ own validation sets using the validation portion of the corpora in Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\") to select the system to submit.\nHowever, we provide the official validation set containing 1000 noisy speech to allow a fair comparison.\nWhen making the official validation set, since many CommonVoice samples are noisy, we manually selected only clean ones.\nSamples from the other datasets are randomly selected after applying the data filtering mentioned in Section [3.3.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.SS3.SSS1 \"3.3.1 Training data ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\").\nThe non-blind test set is made in a similar manner as the official validation set using the test portion of the corpora in Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\").\nHowever, we add some noise and RIRs shown in the shaded cells of Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\") to gauge robustness against unseen data.\n\n#### 3.3.3 Blind test data\n\nThe blind test set, used to determine the final ranking, is primarily from domains unseen during training to assess the robustness and generalizability.\nSpecifically, the blind test set\n\nConsists of 50% simulated data and 50% real recordings, both sourced from publicly available datasets. All synthetic data and most real recordings come from datasets not listed in Table [1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#S3.T1 \"Table 1 ‣ 3.3 Data ‣ 3 Challenge Design ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\"). Since real recordings with certain distortions (e.g., packet loss) are scarce, we artificially apply clipping, packet loss, bandwidth limitations, and codec loss.\n\nIncludes Japanese data as an unseen language.\n\nHas 150 samples per language (totaling 900 samples).\n\nConsiders also unseen distortions due to neural audio codecs, specifically Encodec [[37](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib37)] and Descript Audio Codec [[38](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib38)], as codec lossy distortion in addition to MP3 and OGG.\n\n### 3.4 Two tracks with different data scales\n\nWe provide two tracks with different training data scales but the same test set:\n\nTrack 1: We limit the duration of MLS and CommonVoice, resulting in ∼similar-to\\sim∼2.5k hours of speech.\n\nTrack 2: We do not limit the duration of MLS and CommonVoice datasets, resulting in ∼similar-to\\sim∼60k hours of speech.\n\nThis design allows us to explore (i) the impact of data scale and (ii) data-hungry methods such as large-scale self-supervised-learning-based methods.\n\n### 3.5 Evaluation metrics and ranking strategy\n\nWe use multiple evaluation metrics to perform a more comprehensive evaluation.\nFor instance, the hallucination of a generative model could be hard to detect by non-intrusive metrics but is easily penalized by other metrics888Here, ”hallucination” refers to discrepancies in spoken content or speaker characteristics between the noisy speech and enhanced speech..\nWe adopt the following 14 metrics categorized into five categories:\n\nNon-intrusive SE metrics: DNSMOS [[8](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib8)], NISQA [[16](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib16)], and UTMOS [[17](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib17)].\n\nIntrusive SE metrics: perceptual objective listening quality assessment (POLQA) [[39](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib39)], perceptual evaluation of speech quality (PESQ) [[40](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib40)], extended short-time objective intelligibility (ESTOI) [[41](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib41)], signal-to-distortion ratio (SDR) [[42](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib42)], mel cepstral distortion (MCD) [[43](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib43)], and log-spectral distance (LSD) [[44](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib44)].\n\nDownstream-task-independent metrics: Levenshtein phone similarity (LPS) [[45](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib45)] and SpeechBERTScore (SBS) [[46](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib46)] with mHuBERT-147 [[47](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib47)].\n\nDownstream-task-dependent metrics: speaker similarity (SpkSim) with RawNet3 [[48](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib48)] and character accuracy (CAcc, 1 - character error rate) with OWSM v3.1 [[49](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib49)].\n\nSubjective metric: absolute category rating mean opinion score (MOS) via ITU-T P.808 test [[50](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib50), [51](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib51)], implemented on the Amazon Mechanical Turk (on only English data[2](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#footnote2 \"footnote 2 ‣ 2 Related works ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\")).\n\nCompared to the first challenge [[6](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib6)], we made the following changes to support multilingual data: (i) we use an SSL model trained on multilingual data, mHuBERT-147, in SBS, and (ii) we evaluate CAcc instead of word accuracy.\nIn addition, UTMOS is included, as it showed a high correlation with MOS scores in our preliminary analysis [[7](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib7)].\nPOLQA and MOS were evaluated only in the blind-testing phase.\nThe final ranking is obtained by aggregating the scores of the 14 metrics mentioned above with the following three steps inspired by the Friedman test [[52](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib52)]:\n\nCalculate the ranking for each metric.\n\nAverage the rankings of the metrics in each category.\n\nAverage the category-wise rankings obtained in Step 2.\n\nThe overall ranking scores obtained in Step 3 are used to determine the final ranking.\n\n### 3.6 Baseline system\n\nWe train the TF-GridNet model [[53](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib53)] with around 8.5M parameters on Track1 training data and provide it as the baseline system.\nWe initialize the model with the pre-trained weights provided in the first challenge to save training time.\nTraining takes around 2.5 days using a single NVIDIA RTX A6000 GPU.\nThe training pipeline is based on ESPnet-SE library [[54](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#bib.bib54)]. Please refer to the URGENT challenge website[1](https://arxiv.org/html/2505.23212v2#footnote1 \"footnote 1 ‣ 1 Introduction ‣ Interspeech 2025 URGENT Speech Enhancement Challenge\") for more details.\n\n## 4 Results\n\n| Rank | ID | Model | Non-intrusive SE metrics | | | Intrusive SE metrics | | | | | | Down.-task-indep. | | Down.-task-dep. | | Subject. | Ranking |\n| --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- | --- |\n|  |  | type | DNSMOS↑ | NISQA↑ | UTMOS↑ | POLQA↑ | PESQ↑ | ESTOI↑ | SDR↑ | MCD↓ | LSD↓ | SBS↑ | LPS↑ | SpkSim↑ | CAcc (%)↑ | MOS↑ | score↓ |\n| 1 | T1 | D | 2.88 (8) | 3.22 (6) | 2.09 (5) | 3.40 (1) | 2.64 (1) | 0.82 (1) | 12.66 (1) | 3.67 (2) | 2.93 (3) | 0.87 (1) | 0.74 (1) | 0