20-cVKM&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Frezarassool_basant-mounir-spoke-at-kwaaiday-114-llms-activity-7384372419278520320-cVKM&trk=public_post_like-cta)[Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Frezarassool_basant-mounir-spoke-at-kwaaiday-114-llms-activity-7384372419278520320-cVKM&trk=public_post_comment-cta)\n\n Share \n    *   Copy\n    *   LinkedIn\n    *   Facebook\n    *   X\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Frezarassool_basant-mounir-spoke-at-kwaaiday-114-llms-activity-7384372419278520320-cVKM&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n*   \n[](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/devendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn)\n\n[![Image 15: View profile for Devendra Singh Dhami](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)](https://nl.linkedin.com/in/devendrasinghdhami?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image)[Devendra Singh Dhami](https://nl.linkedin.com/in/devendrasinghdhami?trk=public_post_feed-actor-name)  2mo  Edited    \n\n    *   [Report this post](https://www.linkedin.com/uas/login?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdevendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn&trk=public_post_ellipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\nThe months of September and October have been a bearer of (research-wise) majority good news and some hiccups. 1. 3 contributions to [#NeurIPS](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fneurips&trk=public_post-text) on topics of a novel optimizing technique for realizing Granger causal relations in xLSTMs ([https://lnkd.in/edvtypmp](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fedvtypmp&urlhash=-yil&trk=public_post-text)) formalizing meta-causal models ([https://lnkd.in/eb3D-wiM](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Feb3D-wiM&urlhash=D24D&trk=public_post-text)) by and a novel mixing scheme for xLSTMs proving to be SOTA on time series forecasting ([https://lnkd.in/eTWdTWr9](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FeTWdTWr9&urlhash=qao0&trk=public_post-text)). Note that these are not the final versions of the papers which include more experiments and theoretical analysis for all the 3 papers. Thanks to my collaborators [Harsh Poonia](https://www.linkedin.com/in/harshpoonia?trk=public_post-text), [Felix Divo](https://de.linkedin.com/in/felix-divo?trk=public_post-text), [Maurice Kraus](https://de.linkedin.com/in/maurice-kraus-493199164?trk=public_post-text), [Moritz Willig](https://de.linkedin.com/in/moritz-willig?trk=public_post-text), Tim Woydt, [Kristian Kersting](https://de.linkedin.com/in/kerstingaiml?trk=public_post-text). I will be in San Diego and will be happy to chat. 2. [Florian Busch](https://de.linkedin.com/in/florian-busch-680914215?trk=public_post-text) has a paper in [#TMLR](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Ftmlr&trk=public_post-text) where we propose tractable models (sum-product networks) capable of answering counterfactual queries. This completes the advent of SPNs on the causal ladder i.e. we have SPNs capable of efficient inference on all the 3 rungs of observational, interventional and counterfactual levels. ([https://lnkd.in/ecfPGhpj](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FecfPGhpj&urlhash=p3Ju&trk=public_post-text)) 3. Just had a paper accepted at [#CODS2025](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fcods2025&trk=public_post-text) that sows how statistical relational learning can be helpful in learning a better representation for multi-relational data in context of Graph convolutional networks ([https://lnkd.in/e2tQActK](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fe2tQActK&urlhash=BCpu&trk=public_post-text)). Thanks to my collaborators [Saurabh Mathur](https://de.linkedin.com/in/saurabhmathur96?trk=public_post-text) and [Sriraam Natarajan](https://www.linkedin.com/in/sriraam-natarajan-392a693?trk=public_post-text). 4. Especially proud of this one: [Markus Englberger](https://nl.linkedin.com/in/markus-englberger-7a0675192?trk=public_post-text) (my first PhD student at [Eindhoven University of Technology](https://nl.linkedin.com/school/eindhoven-university-of-technology/?trk=public_post-text)) and I have just put out a paper proposing a new causal framework, driven by category theory, that unifies different notions of causal abstraction. We prove that our work generalizes several previous causal abstraction frameworks ([https://lnkd.in/enEmZ6kn](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FenEmZ6kn&urlhash=4pGn&trk=public_post-text)). Also got a couple of papers rejected in the same timeframe that deal with a novel causal discovery approach and time series summarization. Hope to improve these works and get them out soon. Overall, pretty happy with how the research life is going. Onwards and upwards from here on :)\n\n[![Image 16](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 17](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 18](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) 78](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdevendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)[2 Comments](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdevendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn&trk=public_post_social-actions-comments)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdevendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn&trk=public_post_like-cta)[Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdevendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn&trk=public_post_comment-cta)\n\n Share \n    *   Copy\n    *   LinkedIn\n    *   Facebook\n    *   X\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fdevendrasinghdhami_neurips-tmlr-cods2025-activity-7381317641614880768-monn&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n*   \n[](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/seanjduffy_the-stackle-team-has-been-doing-a-deep-dive-activity-7379704249636614144-Q_MQ)\n\n[![Image 19: View profile for Sean Duffy](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)](https://au.linkedin.com/in/seanjduffy?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image)[Sean Duffy](https://au.linkedin.com/in/seanjduffy?trk=public_post_feed-actor-name)  2mo    \n\n    *   [Report this post](https://www.linkedin.com/uas/login?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fseanjduffy_the-stackle-team-has-been-doing-a-deep-dive-activity-7379704249636614144-Q_MQ&trk=public_post_ellipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\nThe Stackle team has been doing a deep dive into TEQSA's new paper “Enacting assessment reform in a time of artificial intelligence”. One word keeps appearing: \"contextualised.\" Not just \"collect evidence\" - collect it in context. Here's what I'm noticing: A lot of institutions are planning to add more assessment touch points for 2026. More reflection activities, more progress checks, more documentation requirements. But they're adding them to separate systems or tools that are not fit for purpose or built for scale. Which very quickly puts them into workload and scale pain points. During a recent Stackle pilot at University of Newcastle, educators needed evidence of decision-making development - not retrospective journals submitted weeks later. They embedded evidence collection directly into Canvas pages. Students document thinking in the moment, as part of their natural workflow. The engagement rate? 74-80% without requiring it. For those redesigning assessment approaches for 2026 - how are you thinking about \"contextualised\" evidence collection? P.S. If separate systems are creating friction in your evidence collection, let's talk. Stackle embeds it where learning already happens. DM me.\n\n    *   ![Image 20: No alternative text description for this image](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)\n\n[![Image 21](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) 4](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fseanjduffy_the-stackle-team-has-been-doing-a-deep-dive-activity-7379704249636614144-Q_MQ&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fseanjduffy_the-stackle-team-has-been-doing-a-deep-dive-activity-7379704249636614144-Q_MQ&trk=public_post_like-cta)[Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fseanjduffy_the-stackle-team-has-been-doing-a-deep-dive-activity-7379704249636614144-Q_MQ&trk=public_post_comment-cta)\n\n Share \n    *   Copy\n    *   LinkedIn\n    *   Facebook\n    *   X\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fseanjduffy_the-stackle-team-has-been-doing-a-deep-dive-activity-7379704249636614144-Q_MQ&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n*   \n[](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/yu-cao-876b99277_arcmemo-abstract-reasoning-composition-with-activity-7382142816715694082-evSE)\n\n[![Image 22: View profile for Yu Cao](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)](https://de.linkedin.com/in/yu-cao-876b99277?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image)[Yu Cao](https://de.linkedin.com/in/yu-cao-876b99277?trk=public_post_feed-actor-name)  1mo    \n\n    *   [Report this post](https://www.linkedin.com/uas/login?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyu-cao-876b99277_arcmemo-abstract-reasoning-composition-with-activity-7382142816715694082-evSE&trk=public_post_ellipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\nFrom Memory to Mind: Why Self-Generated Graph RAG Could Redefine LLM Intelligence When reading ArcMemo: Abstract Reasoning Composition with Lifelong LLM Memory, one idea struck me deeply — the realization that language models could finally externalize their own hidden knowledge. Instead of storing insights passively inside weights, ArcMemo turns reasoning traces into structured “concept memories,” written in natural language or pseudo-code and reused like modular cognitive blocks. But here’s where it gets exciting: once these concepts are structured, they can easily form a graph — a living network of ideas where each node is a reasoning pattern and each edge encodes how concepts combine or depend on each other. That transforms ArcMemo’s text memories into a Graph-RAG system: instead of retrieving facts, the model retrieves thinking paths. This feels like a crucial leap from retrieval to reflection. By linking its self-generated experiences through a graph, a model could reason not just by recalling similar past cases, but by recombining prior reasoning patterns in new ways — much like how humans form analogies. Graph-based self-RAG may be the missing layer between weights and context: a structured “self-memory” that learns, connects, and evolves with every reasoning step. It’s less about more parameters — and more about better memory. [https://lnkd.in/evb6pFqr](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2Fevb6pFqr&urlhash=YlhN&trk=public_post-text)[#LLMReasoning](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fllmreasoning&trk=public_post-text), [#SelfRAG](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fselfrag&trk=public_post-text), [#GraphMemory](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fgraphmemory&trk=public_post-text), [#ArcMemo](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Farcmemo&trk=public_post-text), [#ConceptAbstraction](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fconceptabstraction&trk=public_post-text), [#LifelongLearning](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Flifelonglearning&trk=public_post-text)\n\n[![Image 23: ArcMemo: Abstract Reasoning Composition with Lifelong LLM Memory](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) ArcMemo: Abstract Reasoning Composition with Lifelong LLM Memory arxiv.org](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Farxiv%2Eorg%2Fabs%2F2509%2E04439v3&urlhash=7BoV&trk=public_post_feed-article-content)\n\n[![Image 24](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) 1](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyu-cao-876b99277_arcmemo-abstract-reasoning-composition-with-activity-7382142816715694082-evSE&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyu-cao-876b99277_arcmemo-abstract-reasoning-composition-with-activity-7382142816715694082-evSE&trk=public_post_like-cta)[Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyu-cao-876b99277_arcmemo-abstract-reasoning-composition-with-activity-7382142816715694082-evSE&trk=public_post_comment-cta)\n\n Share \n    *   Copy\n    *   LinkedIn\n    *   Facebook\n    *   X\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyu-cao-876b99277_arcmemo-abstract-reasoning-composition-with-activity-7382142816715694082-evSE&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n*   \n[](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/arig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz)\n\n[![Image 25: View profile for Aritra Roy Gosthipaty](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)](https://in.linkedin.com/in/arig23498?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image)[Aritra Roy Gosthipaty](https://in.linkedin.com/in/arig23498?trk=public_post_feed-actor-name)  1mo  Edited    \n\n    *   [Report this post](https://www.linkedin.com/uas/login?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Farig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz&trk=public_post_ellipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\nRead and reproduced this paper in a free tier colab notebook. 🔥 Idea: Language models trained on text only, can elicit other sensory knowledge (like vision and audio) when prompted with a sensory cue. For the sake of simplicity I focus on vision only. I use @Alibaba_Qwen \"Qwen/Qwen3-4B\" as the language model and @AIatMeta \"facebook/dinov2-base\" as the vision encoder. Dataset used was 1024-sample WiT dataset. Here is how it went: 1. Encode image using the vision encoder 2. Prompt the language model to generate with a) \"caption\" b)\"imagine: caption\" c) \"imagine seeing: caption\" 3. Encoded the generations 3. Use mutual knn to showcase the alignment Mutual KNN quantifies the similarity of embeddings each in a different latent space based on their neighbours. The authors use mutual knn as a metric to showcase how close are the language and vision embeddings. Thanks to the first author @sophielwang for helping me with the effort.\n\n    *   ![Image 26: No alternative text description for this image](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)\n\n[![Image 27](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 28](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 29](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) 135](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Farig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)[2 Comments](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Farig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz&trk=public_post_social-actions-comments)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Farig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz&trk=public_post_like-cta)[Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Farig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz&trk=public_post_comment-cta)\n\n Share \n    *   Copy\n    *   LinkedIn\n    *   Facebook\n    *   X\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Farig23498_read-and-reproduced-this-paper-in-a-free-activity-7383914234381942784-3grz&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n*   \n[](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/ponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA)\n\n[![Image 30: View profile for Ponnurangam Kumaraguru (PK)](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)](https://in.linkedin.com/in/ponguru?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image)[Ponnurangam Kumaraguru (PK)](https://in.linkedin.com/in/ponguru?trk=public_post_feed-actor-name)  2mo    \n\n    *   [Report this post](https://www.linkedin.com/uas/login?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA&trk=public_post_ellipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\n📢 [#NewPaperAlert](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fnewpaperalert&trk=public_post-text) Excited to share that our paper “A Graph Talks, But Who’s Listening? Rethinking Evaluations for Graph-Language Models” is accepted at the [#NeurIPS2025](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fneurips2025&trk=public_post-text) Workshop on New Perspectives of Graph Machine Learning. Work w/ [Soham Petkar](https://in.linkedin.com/in/sohampetkar?trk=public_post-text), [Hari Aakash K](https://in.linkedin.com/in/hariaakash646?trk=public_post-text), [Anirudh Vempati](https://in.linkedin.com/in/rudy-vempati?trk=public_post-text), [Akshit Sinha](https://uk.linkedin.com/in/akshit-sin?trk=public_post-text)&[Chirag Agarwal](https://www.linkedin.com/in/chirag-agarwal-0a6a43a1?trk=public_post-text) /c [Precog-at-IIITH](https://in.linkedin.com/company/precog-iiith?trk=public_post-text), [NeurIPS](https://www.linkedin.com/company/nipsconference?trk=public_post-text) 🔍 Our key contributions: Show that current GLM benchmarks are insufficient — tasks can be solved with text-only or graph-only signals Provide analysis revealing that unimodal baselines (linear probes, soft prompts) perform on par with GLMs Question the architectural necessity of adding graph encoders to LLMs under current evaluations 📊 What we introduce: CLEGR (Compositional Language-Graph Reasoning), a benchmark explicitly designed to require both text and graph reasoning Covers factual recall, path reasoning, topology, and multi-step compositional inference 🧠 What we find: GLMs saturate on fact-based tasks but collapse on reasoning tasks Even advanced methods like GraphToken, TEA-GLM, and G-Retriever fail to outperform soft-prompted LLMs Highlights the need for more rigorous frameworks to evaluate true graph–language multimodality 💻 🧵 📄 Code & Data, X thread, and Preprint in comments [#GraphML](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fgraphml&trk=public_post-text)[#LanguageModels](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Flanguagemodels&trk=public_post-text)[#MachineLearning](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fmachinelearning&trk=public_post-text)[#MultimodalAI](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fmultimodalai&trk=public_post-text)[#GraphReasoning](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Ffeed%2Fhashtag%2Fgraphreasoning&trk=public_post-text)\n\n    *   ![Image 31: No alternative text description for this image](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)\n\n[![Image 32](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 33](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 34](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) 186](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)[6 Comments](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA&trk=public_post_social-actions-comments)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA&trk=public_post_like-cta)[Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA&trk=public_post_comment-cta)\n\n Share \n    *   Copy\n    *   LinkedIn\n    *   Facebook\n    *   X\n\nTo view or add a comment, [sign in](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fponguru_newpaperalert-neurips2025-graphml-activity-7377557738886770688-4THA&trk=public_post_feed-cta-banner-cta)\n\n*   \n[](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/giuseppefutia_millions-of-textgear-s-extending-graphrag-activity-7386646671658545152-FSvS)\n\n[![Image 35: View profile for Giuseppe Futia, PhD](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)](https://it.linkedin.com/in/giuseppefutia/en?trk=public_post_feed-actor-image)[Giuseppe Futia, PhD](https://it.linkedin.com/in/giuseppefutia/en?trk=public_post_feed-actor-name)  1mo  Edited    \n\n    *   [Report this post](https://www.linkedin.com/uas/login?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fgiuseppefutia_millions-of-textgear-s-extending-graphrag-activity-7386646671658545152-FSvS&trk=public_post_ellipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\n🚀 How to Scale GraphRAG to Millions of Documents? 🧩 Traditional Graph-RAG approaches extract triples (subject, predicate, object) from documents, often via LLMs, to enable multi-hop reasoning over knowledge graphs. But this offline triple extraction step doesn’t scale well to web-scale corpora. 📘 A new paper by [Huawei](https://cn.linkedin.com/company/huawei?trk=public_post-text) and [The University of Edinburgh](https://uk.linkedin.com/school/university-of-edinburgh/?trk=public_post-text), “Millions of GeAR-s: Extending GraphRAG to Millions of Documents”, proposes an elegant alternative: 🔹 Pseudo-alignment instead of extraction Rather than generating new triples, the system performs an online pseudo-alignment between retrieved text chunks and existing Wikidata triples using a combination of dense and sparse retrieval. 🔹 Graph-guided multi-agent reasoning A multi-step (agentic) process decomposes complex queries into simpler sub-questions, traverses the KG to expand reasoning chains, and filters irrelevant passages before generating the final answer. 🔹 Scalable architecture By leveraging external KGs like Wikidata and avoiding heavy LLM extraction, the system scales to millions of passages while retaining graph-enhanced reasoning ability. The paper is available here: [https://lnkd.in/enwgWDte](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Flnkd%2Ein%2FenwgWDte&urlhash=IB3D&trk=public_post-text)\n\n[![Image 36: Millions of $\\text{GeAR}$-s: Extending GraphRAG to Millions of Documents](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) Millions of $\\text{GeAR}$-s: Extending GraphRAG to Millions of Documents arxiv.org](https://www.linkedin.com/redir/redirect?url=https%3A%2F%2Farxiv%2Eorg%2Fabs%2F2507%2E17399v1&urlhash=YCV-&trk=public_post_feed-article-content)\n\n[![Image 37](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 38](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o)![Image 39](https://www.linkedin.com/posts/venkateshcr_interspeech2025-speechaccessibility-asr-activity-7332600736230383618-tz8o) 107](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fgiuseppefutia_millions-of-textgear-s-extending-graphrag-activity-7386646671658545152-FSvS&trk=public_post_social-actions-reactions)[1 Comment](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fgiuseppefutia_millions-of-textgear-s-extending-graphrag-activity-7386646671658545152-FSvS&trk=public_post_social-actions-comments)\n\n[Like](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fgiuseppefutia_millions-of-textgear-s-extending-graphrag-activity-7386646671658545152-FSvS&trk=public_